      {
        "id": 2581464,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-02-10T21:45:03.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group quote-modified\" data-post=\"5\" data-topic=\"149804\">\n<blockquote>\n<p><img src=\"/uploads/db3686/original/2X/4/4030a9a60185376a7393a78002ce3ec0176e975e.gif\" width=\"29\" height=\"33\" alt=\"[help.gif]\" title=\"help\" class=\"animated\"></p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>To give you a more serious answer, this wine is a powerful, tight-knit (and expensive) expression of white Hermitage carrying a considerable overlay of toasty new oak. If you are looking for a classic expression of white Hermitage, this is not it, as the strong wood imprint marks it out very much a contemporary Guigal wine. But if you like the flavors and textures that barrels impart, you will love it. If you want a more traditional white Hermitage, you should seek out Chave\u2019s (which is very textural and unctuous these days) or Marc Sorrel\u2019s.</p>",
        "post_number": 7,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 8,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T09:17:25.735Z",
